PAPER: 107
TITLE: Makumba: a Framework for Rapid and Sustainable Web Development by Amateur Programmers
 
OVERALL RATING: -2 (reject) 
REVIEWER'S CONFIDENCE: 1 (low)  
----------------------- REVIEW --------------------

This paper addresses an interesting issue - the suitability of formal design methods to less-skilled developers, and the role which a simplified framework can play in supporting the development in this case. The authors have undertaken some interesting analysis, though unfortunately the paper is somewhat let down by a tendency to draw conclusions that are not supported by the data - or at least not data that is presented in the paper. For example, the authors state "Our evaluation data shows that Makumba's learning-oriented design plays a crucial role in the Tech Committee sustainability" - and yet data supporting this assertion is not evident. Having sustainable numbers in the so-called "Tech Committee" is not, in the evidence presented, directly connected to the specific architecture, nor is this connection really made clear. Similar concerns also exist with regard to numerous of the other assertions, particularly in the paper discussion. In general the paper discusses int!
 eresting design features of Makumba (though at the level that you might expect to find in a technical report on the system) but does not succeed in connecting these to development practices. Overall the paper makes an interesting case study of application framework development, though not of research into its specific use within a given context. The paper is also marginally over-length, and would benefit from a careful proof-reading. 


