----------------------- REVIEW --------------------

The paper has a promising start, describing a development framework for non-trained programmers that 
"defies" some of the current practices in professional web development.
Unfortunately, the paper does not live up to the expectations.
The decisions behind the technical design of the framework are not well-justified and the paper does not contain enough details to evaluate them. For 
instance, it is not clear what it is the allowed expressivity in the definition of validation rules or whether your data definition allows 
declaring supertypes and subtypes. If it is very limited, your framework can be simple to use but not that useful.
It is not clear at all what you mean by "non-trained programmers". This is misleading because it suggests that people with no programming knowledge can use 
your framework which is not the case. In fact, looking at the learning curve in Fig.1, I don't see why you keep repeating that your framework is so easy to learn.
Section 4 is not much helpful either. Your results suggest that your approach can effectively be used in your domain (universies) but this does not prove that your
framework is a better option than any other option (maybe using another framework you would have obtained the same or better results).
Wrt the discussion section, you say that you enforce a separation between business rules and data views and that this is not enforced in other languages. Maybe PHP does 
not forbid programmers to mix both things but all best-practices guidelines recommend you to do it, so PHP programmers, if working correctly, should obtain the same results. The second
part of the discussion is more interesting even if the trade-offs you mention are already known in the community it is always useful to have some empirical evidence that they are true.
You should compare your framework with other existing lightweight frameworks.
I disagree with your sentence about considering WebML as a strict formalism. I think that web modeling languages in general are quite simple to use since 
they basically use just three different models (data model, navigation model, and presentation model) instead of other UML-based approaches that require
more types of diagrams.
To me, your paper is more valuable as an experience report (where you could explain in more detail the lessons learnt during the process of designing and using the framework) than as a technical
 paper, where
it is not clear what are your contributions. 

